td></mtd><mtd><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">y</mi></mfenced></mtd></mtr></mtable><mo>;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>13</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">y</mi></mrow></mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></mfenced><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><msup><mi>HS</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></mfenced></mrow><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi></mrow></mfenced></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><msup><mi>HS</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><msup><mi>HS</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfrac></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;(<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mo>=</mo></math>negligible)</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><msup><mi>HS</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></msub><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>7</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></mfenced><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></mrow></msup></mfenced></mrow><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><msup><mi>HS</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></mfenced></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></mrow></mfenced><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></mrow></msup></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mstyle><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>7</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></mrow></msup></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></msub><mo>&#215;</mo><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mstyle><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>7</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>13</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mstyle><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>7</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>20</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></math><br />&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (08 Apr)","image":null},{"id":28124,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Equilibrium","question":"","options":["$\\left.\\mathrm{Kc}=\\left[\\mathrm{P}_4 \\mathrm{O}_{10}\\right] / \\mathrm{P}_4\\right]\\left[\\mathrm{O}_2\\right]^5$","$\\mathrm{Kc}=1 /\\left[\\mathrm{O}_2\\right]^5$","$\\mathrm{Kc}=\\left[\\mathrm{O}_2\\right]^5$","$\\mathrm{Kc}=\\left[\\mathrm{P}_4 \\mathrm{O}_{10}\\right] / 5\\left[\\mathrm{P}_4\\right]\\left[\\mathrm{O}_2\\right]$"],"answer":1,"solution":"Applying law of mass action","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2004","image":null},{"id":28013,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Equilibrium","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"Let the initial moles of $N_2O_5$ be $2$.<br><br>The given reaction is:<br>$2N_2O_5(g) \\rightleftharpoons 2N_2O_4(g) + O_2(g)$<br><br>Since $N_2O_5$ is $50\\%$ dissociated (degree of dissociation $\\alpha = 0.5$), the moles at equilibrium are:<br>Moles of $N_2O_5 = 2(1 - 0.5) = 1$<br>Moles of $N_2O_4 = 2(0.5) = 1$<br>Moles of $O_2 = 0.5$<br><br>Total moles at equilibrium $= 1 + 1 + 0.5 = 2.5$<br><br>Given the total pressure $P = 2$ atm, the partial pressures of the gases are:<br>$P_{N_2O_5} = \\dfrac{1}{2.5} \\times 2 = 0.8$ atm<br>$P_{N_2O_4} = \\dfrac{1}{2.5} \\times 2 = 0.8$ atm<br>$P_{O_2} = \\dfrac{0.5}{2.5} \\times 2 = 0.4$ atm<br><br>The equilibrium constant $K_p$ is:<br>$K_p = \\dfrac{(P_{N_2O_4})^2 \\cdot P_{O_2}}{(P_{N_2O_5})^2} = \\dfrac{(0.8)^2 \\times 0.4}{(0.8)^2} = 0.4$<br><br>The standard free energy change $\\Delta G^\\circ$ is given by:<br>$\\Delta G^\\circ = -RT \\ln K_p$<br><br>Using the given values:<br>$\\ln(0.4) = 2.303 \\log(0.4) = 2.303 (\\log 4 - \\log 10)$<br>$\\ln(0.4) = 2.303 (2 \\log 2 - 1) = 2.303 (2 \\times 0.30 - 1) = 2.303 (-0.4) = -0.9212$<br><br>Now, substituting the values into the $\\Delta G^\\circ$ equation ($T = 50^\\circ C + 273 = 323$ K):<br>$\\Delta G^\\circ = -8.314 \\times 323 \\times (-0.9212)$<br>$\\Delta G^\\circ = 2473.81$ J mol$^{-1}$<br><br>The magnitude of the standard free energy change to the nearest integer is $2474$ J mol$^{-1}$.<br><br>Answer: $2474$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (04 April Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":28015,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Equilibrium","question":"","options":["$0.53,0.4$.","$0.742,0.557$.","$0.557,0.418$.","$0.367,0.275$."],"answer":2,"solution":"Initial equilibrium:<br>[A]=0.5 M, [B]=0.375 M; $K_c=\\frac{0.375}{0.5}=0.75$<br>After adding 0.1 mol A: [A]=0.6 M, [B]=0.375 M; Q=0.625<br>Q < Kc, so equilibrium shifts right.<br>Let x be A that decomposes:<br>$\\frac{0.375+x}{0.6-x}=0.75$<br>0.375+x=0.45-0.75x<br>1.75x=0.075; x≈0.0429<br>New [A]=0.6-0.0429=0.557 M; [B]=0.375+0.0429=0.418 M","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (28 January Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":28041,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Equilibrium","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>The given reaction is,</p><p> <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>(</mo><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>⇌</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>(</mo><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>)</mo></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>492</mn><mo> </mo><mi>atm</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>300</mn><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></msub><mo>·</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>RT</mi><msup><mo>)</mo><msub><mi>Δn</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></msub></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Δn</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></msub><mo>=</mo></math> number of gaseous molecules of products – number of gaseous molecules of reactants.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Δn</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math></p><p>By putting the values in the above equation,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>⇒</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></msub><mi>RT</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>492</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>082</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>300</mn></mrow></mfrac><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (29 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":28120,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Equilibrium","question":"","options":["416","$2.40 \\times 10^{-3}$","$9.8 \\times 10^{-2}$","$4.9 \\times 10^{-2}$"],"answer":0,"solution":"$\\begin{aligned} \\mathrm{K}_{\\mathrm{c}}^{\\prime} & =\\left(\\frac{1}{4.9 \\times 10^{-2}}\\right)^2 \\\\ & =\\frac{10^4}{4.9 \\times 4.9}=\\frac{100 \\times 100}{24.01} \\\\ & =4.1649 \\times 100 \\\\ & =416.49\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2006","image":null},{"id":28018,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Equilibrium","question":"","options":["\\(\\begin{array}{c} \\text {(i)} & \\text {(ii)} \\\\ 1,3 & 2,1 \\end{array}\\)","\\(\\begin{array}{c} \\text {(i)} & \\text {(ii)} \\\\ 4,1 & 4,1 \\end{array}\\)","\\(\\begin{array}{c} \\text {(i)} & \\text {(ii)} \\\\ 3,1 & 3,1 \\end{array}\\)","\\(\\begin{array}{c} \\text {(i)} & \\text {(ii)} \\\\ 1,2 & 2,1 \\end{array}\\)"],"answer":3,"solution":"The relationship between $K_p$ and $K_c$ is given by $K_p = K_c(RT)^{\\Delta n_g}$, where $\\Delta n_g = y - x$.<br>Given $T = 400$ K and $R = 0.0821$ L atm K$^{-1}$ mol$^{-1}$.<br>The value of $RT = 0.0821 \\times 400 = 32.84$.<br>For case (i): $K_p = 85.87$ and $K_c = 2.586$.<br>$\\frac{K_p}{K_c} = \\frac{85.87}{2.586} \\approx 33.2$.<br>Since $33.2 \\approx 32.84^1$, we have $\\Delta n_g = y - x = 1$.<br>Checking options for (i):<br>(1) $y-x = 3-1 = 2$<br>(2) $y-x = 1-4 = -3$<br>(3) $y-x = 1-3 = -2$<br>(4) $y-x = 2-1 = 1$. This matches.<br>For case (ii): $K_p = 0.862$ and $K_c = 28.62$.<br>$\\frac{K_p}{K_c} = \\frac{0.862}{28.62} \\approx 0.0301$.<br>Since $0.0301 \\approx \\frac{1}{32.84} = 32.84^{-1}$, we have $\\Delta n_g = y - x = -1$.<br>Checking option (4) for (ii): $y-x = 1-2 = -1$. This also matches.<br>Thus, for (i) $x=1, y=2$ and for (ii) $x=2, y=1$.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (23 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":28050,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Equilibrium","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>The given reaction is exothermic reaction, hence, decreasing temperature is the favourable condition. The change in gaseous moles of products and reactants is negative, hence, increasing pressure is the favourable condition. Addition of reactants and removal of products are the favourable conditions. Catalyst only increase the speed of the reaction.</p><p>The yield of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;at equilibrium will be due to :<br />B. Increasing pressure<br />C. Adding more <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math><br />D. Adding more <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (30 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":28109,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Equilibrium","question":"","options":["$\\frac{\\mathrm{K}_1 \\cdot \\mathrm{K}_2}{\\mathrm{~K}_3}$","$\\frac{\\mathrm{K}_1 \\cdot \\mathrm{K}_3^2}{\\mathrm{~K}_2}$","$\\mathrm{K}_1 \\mathrm{~K}_2 \\mathrm{~K}_3$","$\\frac{\\mathrm{K}_2 \\cdot \\mathrm{K}_3^3}{\\mathrm{~K}_1}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"To calculate the value of $\\mathrm{K}_4$ in the given equation we should apply :\neqn. (2) $+$ eqn. $(3) \\times 3-$ eqn. (1)\nhence $\\mathrm{K}_4=\\frac{\\mathrm{K}_2 \\mathrm{~K}_3^3}{\\mathrm{~K}_1}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (23 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":28075,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Equilibrium","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>/</mo><mn>64</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>8</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>/</mo><mn>4</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>/</mo><mn>8</mn></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></mfenced><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8652;</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msup><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mrow><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfenced><msup><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>3</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>64</mn></math></p><p>For the reaction</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8652;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></mfenced><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><msub><mo>'</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msup><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfenced><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>/</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><msup><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfenced><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>/</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfenced></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msqrt><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></msub></msqrt></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msqrt><mn>64</mn></msqrt></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>8</mn></mfrac></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (06 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":28117,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Equilibrium","question":"","options":["The concentration of $\\mathrm{CO}_3^{2-}$ is $0.034 \\mathrm{M}$.","The concentration of $\\mathrm{CO}_3^{2-}$ is greater than that of $\\mathrm{HCO}_3^{-}$.","The concentration of $\\mathrm{H}^{+}$and $\\mathrm{HCO}_3^{-}$are approximately equal.","The concentration of $\\mathrm{H}^{+}$is double that of $\\mathrm{CO}_3^{2-}$."],"answer":2,"solution":"$\\begin{array}{lll}\\mathrm{A} \\rightarrow & \\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{CO}_3 \\rightleftharpoons \\mathrm{H}^{+}+\\mathrm{HCO}_3^{-} & \\mathrm{K}_1=4.2 \\times 10^{-7} \\\\ \\mathrm{~B} \\rightarrow & \\mathrm{HCO}_3^{-} \\rightleftharpoons \\mathrm{H}^{+}+\\mathrm{CO}_3^{-2} & \\mathrm{~K}_2=4.8 \\times 10^{-11}\\end{array}$\nAs $\\mathrm{K}_2 \\ll \\mathrm{K}_1$\nAll major $\\left[\\mathrm{H}^{+}\\right]_{\\text {todal }} \\approx\\left[\\mathrm{H}^{+}\\right]_{\\mathrm{A}}$\nand from I equilibrium, $\\left[\\mathrm{H}^{+}\\right]_{\\mathrm{A}} \\approx\\left[\\mathrm{HCO}_3^{-}\\right] \\approx\\left[\\mathrm{H}^{+}\\right]_{\\text {tocal }}$\n$\\left[\\mathrm{CO}_3^{-2}\\right]$ is negligible compared to $\\left[\\mathrm{HCO}_3^{-}\\right]$or $\\left[\\mathrm{H}^{+}\\right]_{\\text {total }}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2010","image":null},{"id":28115,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Equilibrium","question":"","options":["$0.02$","$2.5 \\times 10^2$","$4 \\times 10^{-4}$","$50.0$"],"answer":3,"solution":"$\\begin{array}{ll}\\mathrm{N}_2+\\mathrm{O}_2 \\rightleftharpoons 2 \\mathrm{NO} & \\mathrm{K}_{\\mathrm{C}}=4 \\times 10^{-4} \\\\ \\mathrm{NO} \\rightleftharpoons \\frac{1}{2} \\mathrm{~N}_2+\\frac{1}{2} \\mathrm{O}_2 & \\mathrm{~K}_{\\mathrm{C}}^1=\\sqrt{\\frac{1}{\\mathrm{~K}_{\\mathrm{C}}}} \\\\ \\mathrm{K}_{\\mathrm{C}}^1=\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{4 \\times 10^{-4}}}=50 & \\end{array}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (Offline)","image":null},{"id":28093,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Equilibrium","question":"","options":["$2.5$","4","2","3"],"answer":0,"solution":"Initially 2 moles of $\\mathrm{CO}$ are present.\nAt equilibrium, 1 mole of $\\mathrm{CO}$ is present Hence, $2-1=1$ moles of $\\mathrm{CO}$ has reacted. 1 mole of CO will react with 1 mole of $\\mathrm{Cl}_2$ to form 1 mole of $\\mathrm{COCl}_2$. $3-1=2$ moles of $\\mathrm{Cl}_2$ remains at equilibrium The equilibrium constant\n$$\nK_{\\mathrm{c}}=\\frac{\\left[\\mathrm{COCl}_2\\right]}{[\\mathrm{CO}]\\left[\\mathrm{Cl}_2\\right]}=\\frac{\\frac{1 \\mathrm{~mol}}{5 \\mathrm{~L}}}{\\frac{1 \\mathrm{~mol}}{5 \\mathrm{~L}} \\times \\frac{2 \\mathrm{~mol}}{5 \\mathrm{~L}}}=2.5\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (15 Apr Shift 2 Online)","image":null},{"id":28028,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Equilibrium","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/EHuRVlJv5PVglar5pPR-9rX7urGmYNIjk5n5Q-aSNEI.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/C3I-LlYJxghk95sc8TESX0pCoPtTiEtfsX_pkiEKGSo.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/pA88HOHMcrsyEWrxc1Rf0wJcssqX6MvZJbGGHol8DSQ.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/kl70pCNn9mBFDaUlZzstrbMCKD11PrwIHChwybUrt9g.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>"],"answer":1,"solution":"$\\mathrm{H}_2(\\mathrm{~g})+\\mathrm{I}_2(\\mathrm{~g}) \\rightleftharpoons 2 \\mathrm{HI}(\\mathrm{~g})$\nConcentrations of $\\mathrm{H}_2(\\mathrm{~g})$ and $\\mathrm{I}_2(\\mathrm{~g})$ decrease with time while concentration of $\\mathrm{HI}(\\mathrm{g})$ increases with time. At equilibrium $\\mathrm{H}_2(\\mathrm{~g}), \\mathrm{I}_2(\\mathrm{~g})$ and $\\mathrm{HI}(\\mathrm{g})$ attain constant values. Correct plot of molar concentration with time is","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (24 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":28123,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Equilibrium","question":"","options":["$0.30$","$0.18$","$0.17$","$0.11$"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/Kvaw0RT8zSGaN36SL60ZA_lD0fudaidmAR4c7D8cXcU.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\nTotal pressure $=0.5+2 \\mathrm{x}=0.84$\ni.e., $\\mathrm{x}=0.17$\n$\\mathrm{~K}_{\\mathrm{p}}=\\mathrm{p}_{\\mathrm{NH}_3} \\cdot \\mathrm{p}_{\\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{~s}}$\n$=(0.67) .(0.17)$\n$\\quad=0.1139$.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2005","image":null},{"id":28081,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Equilibrium","question":"","options":["leaves the vapour&nbsp;increases","leaves the solution increases","leaves the solution decreases","leaves the vapour decreases"],"answer":0,"solution":"The vapour pressure of solution will be less than vapour pressure of pure solvent, so some vapour molecules will get condensed to maintain new equilibrium.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (02 Sep Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":28130,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Equilibrium","question":"","options":["$2 \\mathrm{NH}_3 \\rightarrow \\mathrm{N}_2+3 \\mathrm{H}_2$","$\\mathrm{C}(\\mathrm{g})+(1 / 2) \\mathrm{O}_2(\\mathrm{~g}) \\rightarrow \\mathrm{CO}(\\mathrm{g})$","$\\mathrm{H}_2(\\mathrm{~g})+\\mathrm{O}_2(\\mathrm{~g}) \\rightarrow \\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{O}_2(\\mathrm{~g})$","none of these"],"answer":3,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2002","image":null}]